An Analysis of the Age of Contestants and Viewership of the Great British Baking Show

Kasey Turtell

2023 - 03 - 06

Introduction

The Great British Bake Off is an internationally beloved British baking show, consisting of several competitions between amateur bakers. Each season, or series as they are referred to by the British, begins with 12 bakers, with one being eliminated from the show by the judges after every episode for the ten episodes. The judges are Paul Hollywood, who is trained in both sculpting and baking, allowing him to become a pioneer in the baking field, and Prue Leith, the founder of a culinary school that has produced multiple other famous chefs. The show is hosted by two comedians and actors, Noel Fielding and Matt Lucas. The first series of the show aired in 2010, and in my analysis, I will explore the first ten series, spanning from 2010 to 2019, but the show has had several seasons since. The Great British Bake Off has become not only popular in its home country of the United Kingdom but all over the world; possibly because of its comforting nature. The bakers compete outdoors, in a tent, surrounded by a field of flowers, and while they are in a stress filled competition consisting of 3 different challenges (the Signature Bake, the Technical Challenge, and the Showstopper Bake), there is a sense of coziness that the show brings to viewers.

In this analysis, I used a data set called “Great British Bakeoff,” which contains information about the challenges, bakers, ratings, and episodes, in addition to more detailed information when these topics are broken down. In my analysis, I use the data set called “bakers,” which contains information about the series number each baker appeared, their name, the number of time they’ve one each challenge, their age, etc. and the data set called “ratings” which contains the viewership information for each episode of each series of the show. The analysis I wish to conduct is a review of the correlation between the average age of the contestants on the show and its viewership ratings.

The packages that were used in my exploration were tidyverse and ggplot2. I also installed a package called “bakeoff” and stored it using the library( ) function. I used the tidyverse package in order to make tibbles and to tidy my data and I used ggplot2 to create graph that visually represent my analysis.

Data Preparation

The data set was obtained from the following link: https://github.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/tree/master/data/2022/2022-10-25#great-british-bakeoff. This data was obtained by Alison Hill, Chester Ismay, and Richard Iannone. Even though it is not outright stated, it seems that those who collected the data acquired it by watching the first ten seasons of the Great British Bake Off and tracking all of the information themselves that they could, it is not stated where the ratings information came from but it can be assumed that it came from the network on which the show airs, BBC. The original “bakers” data set included the variables:

  • series - a double representing the season/series number

  • bakers - a character representing the baker’s name)

  • star_baker - an integer representing how many times the baker was named star baker

  • technical_winner - an integer representing how many times the baker won the technical challenge

  • technical_top3 - an integer representing how many times the baker ranked in the top 3 of the technical challenge

  • technical_bottom - an integer representing how many times the baker was ranked in the bottom of the technical challenge

  • technical_highest - a double representing how many times the baker was ranked highest in the technical challenge

  • technical_lowest - a double representing how many times the baker was ranked lowest in the technical challenge

  • technical_median - a double representing how many times the baker was ranked as the median in the technical challenge

  • series_winner - an integer representing how many times the baker was named the winner of the series

  • series_runner_up - an integer representing how many times the baker was named the runner up of the series

  • total_episodes_appeared - a double representing the total number of episodes on which the baker appeared

  • first_date_appeared - a double representing the date of the episode on which the baker first appeared

  • last_date_appeared - a double representing the date of the episode on which the baker last appeared

  • first_date_us - a double representing the date of the episode on which the baker first appeared when aired in the United States

  • last_date_us - a double representing the date of the episode on which the baker last appeared when aired in the United States

  • percent_episodes_appeared - a double representing the percentage of episodes that the baker appeared in

  • percent_technical_top3- a double representing the percent of the challenges in which the baker was in the top 3 of the technical challenge

  • baker_full - a character representing the baker’s full name

  • age - a double representing the baker’s age

  • occupation - a character representing the baker’s occupation

  • hometown - a character representing the baker’s hometown

  • baker_last - a character representing the baker’s last name

  • baker_first - a character representing the baker’s first name The original “ratings” data set included the variables:

  • series - a double representing the season/series number

  • episode - a double representing the episode number

  • uk_airdate - a double representing the date that the episode aired in the United Kingdom

  • viewers_7day - a double representing the number of viewers over a 7 day period (in millions)

  • viewers_28day - a double representing the number of viewers over a 28 day period (in millions)

  • network_rank - a double representing the rank of the episode given by the network

  • channels_rank - a double representing the rank of the episode given by the channel

  • bb_iplayer_requests - double representing the amount of BBC iPlayer (a British streaming service) requests

  • episode_count - a double representing the episode count

  • us_season - a double representing the number of the season in the United States

  • us_airdate - a character representing the date that the episode aired in the United States

In order to begin my analysis, I had to tidy the data and create new variables that had only the data that was necessary for my exploration. First, I wanted to get the average age of the bakers in each season. To do this, I made the data set “bakers” into a tibble, then used the select( ) function in order to make the new “bakers” tibble only have the data for series and the ages. I then used the aggregate( ) function to get the mean age of the bakers of the same series and replace that as the tibble called bakers, I finally changed the column names to appropriately represent the variables, and used the head( ) function to check my work.

bakers <- as_tibble(bakers)

bakers <- bakers %>%
  select(series, age)

bakers <- aggregate(bakers$age, list(bakers$series), mean)
colnames(bakers)[1] <- "series"
colnames(bakers)[2] <- "average age"

ratings <- aggregate(ratings[2:4], list(ratings$series), mean)

Breakdown of the Data Analysis

Graph Type One: Scatter Plot

I chose a scatter plot as my first graph because I felt that could directly represent the relationship between the average age of contestants per series and the viewers per series. To make this plot, I named it gbb_scatter and used the plot( ) function, beginning with the variable of ratings (viewers_7day) in the y-axis, using the pch the change the shape of the point on graph, the “col =” to change the color of the points, the “ylim =” to change the size of the graph, and “xlab =” and “ylab =” to change the labels on the graph. I then added a line of best fit in the same color as the points using the abline(lm( )) functions. To add the data for the other variables of the ratings tibble, I used the points( ) function, then made each variable the y-axis, keeping the x-axis the average age of contestants. I changed the color and point shape for each variable to make the plot more visibly interesting and allow for the viewer to be able to distinguish between the relationships of the different variables. I then added a title to the graph using title( ). And finally, I added a legend, using legend( ), adding the color each variable represents and “cex =” to change the size of the legend in order to properly fit the graph.

gbb_scatter <- plot(gbb$`average age`, gbb$viewers_7day, pch = 15, col = "maroon", ylim = c(0,14), xlab = "Average Age Per Series", ylab = "Average Viewers per Series")
    abline(lm(gbb$viewers_7day ~ gbb$`average age`), col = "maroon")
  points(gbb$`average age`, gbb$viewers_28day, pch = 16, col = "purple2")
    abline(lm(gbb$viewers_28day ~ gbb$`average age`), col="purple2")
  points(gbb$`average age`, gbb$network_rank, pch = 17, col = "pink1")
    abline(lm(gbb$network_rank ~ gbb$`average age`), col= "pink1")
  title("Average Age vs Viewer Ratings of the Great British Bake Off")
  legend("topleft", cex = .8,
         legend = c("Viewers Over 7 Days", "Viewers Over 28 Days", "Network Rank"),
         lwd = 3, col = c("maroon", "purple2", "pink1"))

From the graph, it can be clearly seen that there is no correlation between the average age of the contestants on the show and the viewership. Not only are most of the the points seemingly random, with no strong correlation, the lines of correlation have conflicting slopes, suggesting no relationship between the independent and dependent variables.

Graph Type Two: Bar Plot

I created two bar plots, one to represent the ratings and one to represent the ages of the bakers. I began with the bar plot to represent the ratings data. First, I used the par(mfrow =) function to put the two bar plots side by side (I could not use grid.arrage( ) because the barplot( ) is not a ggplot2 function). I created a variable called “ratingsbyseries” using the group_by( ) function to group the ratings data by series. I then used the as_tibble( ) function to force it into a tibble, used the summarize( ) function to get all of the data that I needed into the tibble, and then in order to put the information into the bar plot, I had to make it into a matrix. For aesthetic purposes, I used colorRampPalette to create a gradient of colors from “azure2” to “navyblue”, calling it “seriescolors” and I tested it by typing seriescolors(10), which would give ten colors including and between the two of the desired gradient. To create the actual bar plot, I created the variable “gbb_bar1”, assigning it to be barplot( ) with the x-value being the “ratingsseries”, having the bars beside each other (represented by “beside = TRUE”), creating a legend (using “legend = TRUE”), creating a label for the y-axis, making my gradient I made earlier the colors of the bars, and I used “cex.names =” to change the size of the text for the label of the y-axis. I then added the text for the legend and the corresponding colors as well as a title, using “cex.man =” to change the size of the text of the title. I used a similar technique to create the second bar plot, representing age.

# to put the two plots side by side
  par(mfrow = c(1:2))
# the first bar plot : ratings 
ratingsbyseries <- group_by(ratings, series)
ratingsbyseries <- as_tibble(ratingsbyseries)
ratingsbyseries <- summarize(ratingsbyseries, viewers_7day, viewers_28day, network_rank)
## Warning: Returning more (or less) than 1 row per `summarise()` group was deprecated in
## dplyr 1.1.0.
## ℹ Please use `reframe()` instead.
## ℹ When switching from `summarise()` to `reframe()`, remember that `reframe()`
##   always returns an ungrouped data frame and adjust accordingly.
ratingsbyseries <- as.matrix(ratingsbyseries)

seriescolors <- colorRampPalette(c("azure2", "navyblue"))
seriescolors(10)
##  [1] "#E0EEEE" "#C7D3E1" "#AEB9D5" "#959EC9" "#7C84BD" "#6369B0" "#4A4FA4"
##  [8] "#313498" "#181A8C" "#000080"
gbb_bar1 <- barplot(ratingsbyseries, beside = TRUE, legend = TRUE, ylab = "Average Viewers Per Series", col = seriescolors(10), cex.names = .5)
  legend("topright", cex = .4,
         legend = c("Series 1", "Series 2","Series 3","Series 4","Series 5","Series 6","Series 7","Series 8","Series 9","Series 10"),
         lwd = 2, col = seriescolors(10))
  title("Average Viewers of the Great British Bake Off", cex.main = .6)
# the second bar plot : ages
agebyseries <- group_by(bakers, series)
agebyseries <- as_tibble(agebyseries)
agebyseries <- as.matrix(agebyseries)
agebyseries <- agebyseries[,-1]

agecolors <- colorRampPalette(c("deeppink4", "lightpink1"))

gbb_bar2 <- barplot(agebyseries, beside = TRUE, legend = TRUE, ylab = "Average Age Per Series", col = agecolors(10), cex.names = .6)
  legend("bottomright", inset(-.02, -.03), cex = .45,
       legend = c("Series 1", "Series 2","Series 3","Series 4","Series 5","Series 6","Series 7","Series 8","Series 9","Series 10"),
       lwd = 2, col = agecolors(10))
  title("Average Age of the Contestants on the Great British Bake Off", cex.main = .5)

When comparing the plots, the observers can see that there is no correlation between the viewers of the show and the age of the contestants. The two bar plots do not follow the same pattern of increasing or decreasing as series increase or decrease, implying that there is no relationship between the amount in viewers of the Great British Bake Off and the average age of the contestants.

Graph Type Three: Pairwise Scatter Plot

The final type of graph that I chose to use in my analysis was a pairwise scatter plot, once again because I felt that it could easily and elegantly show the relationship between the ratings and age of the bakers. I then created a new variable called “gbb_pairs” which contains both the bakers’ average ages and ratings information, without the series information using the select( ) function, keeping only the variables that I have previously stated. I also created a variable called “pairscolors” and assinged it to the gradient of colors between “plum” and “darkorchid4” using colorRampPalette. I then used this data and replaced the variable gbb_pairs as the pairwise scatter plot of the data using the pairs( ) function. For aesthetic purposes, I used “col =” to assign the gradient I previously created to the colors of the graph and I created a title.

gbb_pairs <- gbb %>%
  select(`average age`, viewers_7day, viewers_28day, network_rank)
pairscolors <- colorRampPalette(c("plum", "darkorchid4"))

gbb_pairs <- pairs(gbb_pairs, col = pairscolors(10))
  title("Average Age and Viewership of the Great British Baking Show")

The pairwise scatter plot shows, just as the other plots do, that there is no correlation between the average age of the contestants, the amount of viewers over a 7 day period, the amount of viewers over a 28 day period, and the network rank. The points on the plot seem to be at random and have no real relationship between the variables.

Summary

In my analysis, I wanted to explore the relationship between the average age of the contestants on the Great British Bake Off and the amount of ratings of the show. The data that I used ranged from the first 10 series/season of the show, from 2010 to 2019. Prior to beginning my examination of the data, I thought that there may have been a change in viewership based on age because different populations were being represented in the show, and therefore different people were gaining and losing interest based on who they saw on screen. However, upon inquiry into the statistics, I found that there is no correlation between the average age of contestants on the Great British Bake Off and the amount of viewers and ratings based off of the first ten series.
